50|$|In 1825, he {{successfully}} {{continued his}} {{studies at the}} School of Pharmacy of Paris. He then returned to his shop in Saint-Étienne. He invented a gas regulator and a <b>firedamp</b> <b>detector</b> which were not retained by the manufacturers.|$|E
50|$|He is {{best remembered}} for his studies {{of blood and}} blood {{circulation}} (measurement of cardiac output in animals) and respiration. He also made contributions in his research of the nervous system, of muscle activity, toxicology, anaesthesia and experimental hygiene. He developed a number of devices that he used in research, including a grisoumètre (<b>firedamp</b> <b>detector)</b> that was still in use in coal mines up until 1950.|$|E

